player.seasonOutlook: Anderson's 2018 was a tale of two stories. Anderson signed with Carolina during the offseason and was limited to 128 yards on 25 touches across nine games as Christian McCaffrey's backup. He signed with the Rams later in the year and went on to explode for 522 yards and four scores on 96 touches in only five games (including the playoffs). With Todd Gurley sidelined, Anderson paced all backs in fantasy points during Weeks 16-17. Anderson, who has ranked in the upper two-thirds at the position in YAC during four of his five NFL seasons, now joins the Lions, where he'll work alongside versatile Kerryon Johnson. LeGarrette Blount (no longer with the Lions) averaged 8.1 carries per game in this role last season, and we should anticipate something similar for Anderson. The 28-year-old has some handcuff appeal in Detroit's run-first offense.

Peterson's 2018 prospects seemed dim during most of last offseason, but Derrius Guice's torn ACL allowed the former fantasy star one more shot at lead back duties. Peterson held down the fort, finishing fifth in the league with 251 carries and averaging 4.2 yards per carry. As usual, Peterson played a minimal role as a receiver (26 targets) but scored enough touchdowns (eight) to manage a 19th-place finish in fantasy points. Peterson re-signed with Washington, but assuming Guice is healthy, the 2018 second-round pick will be the team's primary back. The 34-year-old Peterson will have flex value only if Guice misses time.

Williams has struggled with efficiency during his first two NFL seasons, but he has still managed to register 921 snaps and 326 touches during that span. The 2017 fourth-round pick increased his rookie-season 3.6 YPC to 3.8 in 2018, but his YAC fell from 1.9 to 1.7. That is despite facing extremely light boxes both seasons. Williams has also ranked near the bottom of the position in catch rate (73 percent) on 71 career targets. Though he'll sustain a role in the Packers' backfield, Williams won't see enough volume to allow fantasy relevance as long as the more effective Aaron Jones is healthy.

Smith was selected in the fourth round of last year's draft and spent most of his rookie season working in a situational role behind Tevin Coleman. Smith wasn't particularly impressive, managing only 315 yards and four scores on 90 carries (3.5 YPC, 1.4 YAC) and 27 receptions for 152 yards on 32 targets. His 5.6 YPR was dead last at running back. Smith is positioned for a similar role in 2019, this time as a change-of-pace back behind Devonta Freeman. Smith has minimal standalone value, but is Freeman's likely handcuff in an offense that is rarely short on points.

Looking to fill a need after the offseason departure of Latavius Murray, Minnesota selected Mattison with the No. 102 pick in April's draft. Mattison is a big, between-the-tackles back at 5-foot-11, 221 pounds, but also has good receiving and blocking chops. Mattison, who handled a whopping 302 carries at Boise State last season, lacks speed (4.67 YPC) and quickness, but has the size and skill set to settle in as a reliable backup. That's the role he'll play in 2019 as Dalvin Cook's handcuff.

A relatively unheralded prospect, Edwards went undrafted in 2018 before eventually storming onto the fantasy scene around midseason. From Week 11 on, Edwards averaged 17.4 carries per game, though he was targeted only once. On 137 carries for the season, Edwards averaged 5.2 YPC (eighth-best), including 2.1 YAC (17th-best). Edwards scored only two touchdowns, and his nonexistent receiving role limited him to one weekly fantasy finish better than 19th. Edwards is now behind Mark Ingram II on the depth chart and, though he could still push for more than 100 carries in Baltimore's run-heavy offense, he won't see many (any?) targets and, thus, is no more than a low-ceiling Ingram handcuff.

Edmonds was selected in the fourth round of the 2018 draft and quickly earned No. 2 duties behind workhorse David Johnson. Edmonds was held to 208 yards and a pair of touchdowns on 60 carries (3.5 YPC, 1.5 YAC) and 103 yards on 23 targets (4.5 YPT). The 23-year-old didn't stand out as a rookie but remains positioned as Johnson's primary handcuff, which supplies him with value in deeper leagues.

Gore joins the Bills as a complement to LeSean McCoy after a bizarre 2018 season in Miami, during which he averaged a healthy 4.6 YPC (2.3 YAC), but failed to rush for a single touchdown. Gore finished 46th at the position in fantasy points, which is the first time he has finished a season worse than 21st since 2006. He also missed a game for the first time since 2010. Now 36 years old, Gore won't see enough volume to allow consistent fantasy production. Even if McCoy were to miss time, Gore would share touches with TJ Yeldon and rookie Devin Singletary. There's almost zero fantasy appeal here.

Detroit selected Hockenson eighth overall in April's draft. The Iowa product joins free-agent signing Jesse James atop the Lions' depth chart. Hockenson is a terrific pass catcher and good blocker who has drawn comparisons to Travis Kelce, Rob Gronkowski and even former Hawkeye George Kittle. Hockenson is a superb athlete, with good size (6-foot-5, 251 pounds) and toughness. He crushed it at the combine, placing near the top of the position in all but the bench press. Hockenson has every-down tight end written all over him, but, as is usual for rookie tight ends, he figures to learn the ropes in 2019 before emerging as a fantasy threat in 2020. Hockenson doesn't need to be on your radar in 10-team leagues in 2019.

Denver selected Fant with the No. 20 pick in April's draft. Fant has a ways to go as a blocker and needs to cut down on drops, but he's a terrific receiver who will operate as an F/move tight end in the pros. Fant is 6-foot-4, 249 pounds and a terrific athlete with good speed and production near the end zone. He was tops at the position in the 40-yard-dash (4.50), vertical (39.5 inches), broad jump (127 inches), three cone (6.81) and 60-yard shuttle (11.49) at the combine. Fant figures to begin his career in a time-share with Jake Butt and Jeff Heuerman, but could make some noise in fantasy as the season progresses. He's not a bad late flier in deeper leagues.

Carr is entering his sixth NFL season and has yet to post a top-10 fantasy campaign. The 28-year-old appeared in all 16 games last season, but still managed a finish of just 18th thanks to a career-low 19 passing touchdowns. Granted he was conservative (career-low 6.9 aDOT), but Carr posted career-best marks in completion percentage (69 percent), off-target rate (10.1 percent) and yards per attempt (7.3), while throwing only 10 interceptions (1.8 percent rate). The off-target rate was best in the NFL. Carr's prospects are certainly improved in 2019 with the likes of Antonio Brown, Tyrell Williams and J.J. Nelson added to an overhauled receiving core. That supplies Carr with some sleeper appeal, but quarterback is deep and he offers little with his legs. He's a fringe QB2.

After posting a pair of top-35 fantasy seasons during the previous three seasons, Ginn appeared on his way to another in 2018 prior to suffering a Week 4 knee injury. Through three weeks, Ginn's 12/135/2 line was enough to allow him the 40th-most fantasy points at the position. He had been on the field for 74 percent of New Orleans' pass plays, which was his highest rate since 2009. Ginn led all wide receivers with a 77 percent catch rate in 2017. He's now 34 years old and second-year Tre'Quan Smith looms, but Ginn could push for flex production if he picks up where he left off in last season's playoffs as the No. 2 wide receiver in the Saints' high-scoring offense.

The Cardinals drafted Butler in the fourth round of April's draft. The former Iowa State star is a massive 6-foot-5, 227 pounds with huge hands (10.8 inches) and an 83.9-inch wingspan, the latter of which was biggest among combine wide receivers. He has a good combination of speed (4.48 40-yard dash) and strength (18 bench reps), which helped him average 22.0 yards per reception on 60 catches last season. Butler lacks some short-area quickness and his biggest red flag is drops (he paced this year's rookie crop with 12 last season). He has a high ceiling, but Butler will have his hands full finding targets this season with Larry Fitzgerald and fellow youngsters Christian Kirk, Andy Isabella and KeeSean Johnson all in the fold. Target him late in deep leagues.

Cobb signed with the Cowboys after spending the first eight seasons of his career with the Packers. Cobb peaked with a 91/1287/12 line (WR8 in fantasy) in 2014, but his production has progressively dropped over the past four seasons. Injuries have been a problem throughout Cobb's career, as he has managed only two 16-game regular seasons and has missed 11 games over the past three seasons. Solely a short-area target, Cobb has ranked near the bottom of the league in aDOT in each of his eight seasons. He'll replace Cole Beasley in the slot in Dallas and doesn't figure to offer many big downfield plays or touchdowns. Likely fourth in line for targets, the 28-year-old Cobb is only worth a late-round flier.

Parker's days in Miami appeared numbered following a career-worst 2018 season in which he was held to a 24/306/1 line in 11 games. A coaching change reversed his fortunes, however, and Parker re-signed through 2020. The 2015 first-round pick has not lived up to lofty expectations. He has yet to put together a full 16-game season, missing 11 games during his four seasons. He has scored nine touchdowns in 53 games and his best fantasy campaign was a 50th-place finish in 2016. The 26-year-old's top competition for snaps and targets is Kenny Stills, Albert Wilson and Jakeem Grant, so he has a shot to get his career back on track. It's a long shot, of course, so consider him in only very deep leagues.

A second-round pick in 2017, Jones' NFL career started poorly with a 27/316/2 line on 68 rookie-season targets. He ranked dead last in both catch rate (40 percent) and YPT (4.6). Granted, the bar was low, but he did take a step forward in 2018, posting a 56/652/7 line on 100 targets. His 56 percent catch rate and 6.5 YPT again ranked near the bottom of the league and his 2.5 RAC (fourth worst) was actually down from 2.7 in 2017. Jones' heavy volume (27th in targets) and boost in scoring (13th in touchdowns) allowed him a 35th-place finish in fantasy points, but the efficiency woes can't be ignored. That's especially the case with inaccurate Josh Allen under center and with Cole Beasley and John Brown added to the mix. Jones no longer has a clear path to a starting role and is worth only a flier in very deep leagues.

Enunwa returns to the Jets after a roller-coaster ride of production in recent seasons. Enunwa broke out with a 58/857/4 line in 2016 (his third NFL season) before missing all of 2017 with a neck injury. He seemed en route to a bounce-back campaign last season, registering eight-plus targets in each of his first four games, but was limited to 4.6 targets per game while battling injuries the rest of the season. Enunwa is now 27 years old, has played more than 12 games in a season once and has finished one season better than 84th in fantasy points. His outlook is helped by new coach Adam Gase (Dolphins WRs ranked 10th in fantasy points during his three seasons as head coach), but the ceiling here is low in a suddenly-crowded offense. He's barely worth draft-day consideration.

Darnold was a 21-year-old Week 1 starter for a Jets offense lacking a good supporting cast last season. It showed. The 2018 third-overall pick struggled to a 58 percent completion percentage (third worst) and 6.9 yards per attempt (10th worst), though part of that can be attributed to a 9.4 aDOT (fourth highest). Working behind a weak offensive line, Darnold was pressured on 25 percent of his dropbacks (sixth most), took 30 sacks and missed three games with an injury. On the plus side, Darnold finished strong once healthy, posting six TDs and just one INT with a 7.4 YPA during his final four games. The youngster will have more help and a new coaching staff in 2019, so it's fair to expect another step forward. He's a back-end QB2 and breakout candidate.

To this point, the Garoppolo experiment has not worked out for San Francisco. The former Patriot was acquired during the 2017 season, but has appeared in only nine games due to injury. In fact, the 27-year-old has yet to appear in more than six games in a regular season. Garoppolo's play has also left something to be desired. In nine games with the 49ers, he's contributed 13 touchdowns, thrown 8 interceptions and fumbled 5 times. His production is almost exactly identical to that posted by 2017 undrafted free agent Nick Mullens in eight games last season. Garoppolo remains a bit of an unknown, but his combination of talent and the presence of head coach Kyle Shanahan offers him fantasy upside. He's a back-end QB2 and post-hype sleeper.

The Eagles' D/ST finished as a top-six fantasy unit in Doug Pederson's first two seasons with the team but plummeted to 26th last season. The Eagles struggled in nearly every area, falling from fourth in forced turnovers, yardage allowed and points allowed in 2017 to 22nd, 23rd and 12th, respectively, last season. They didn't score a D/ST touchdown after managing at least five in each of the previous four seasons. The Eagles lost Jordan Hicks, Michael Bennett and Haloti Ngata but added Malik Jackson, Vinny Curry, Andrew Sendejo and Zach Brown in the offseason. The newcomers join a group led by Fletcher Cox, Malcolm Jenkins and Brandon Graham. This is a good defense and prime rebound candidate. A Week 1 home matchup with Washington adds to the unit's draft appeal.

Cleveland's D/ST finished 2018 25th in fantasy points, which was an improvement on the previous three seasons. Although 25th doesn't sound good, it doesn't tell the whole picture. Cleveland allowed 6,288 yards (third-most), surrendered 392 points (12th-most) and failed to score a non-offensive touchdown but intercepted 17 passes (fifth-most), forced 18 fumbles (sixth-most), posted 75 passes defensed (fifth-most) and had 101 tackles for loss (fifth-most). They ranked 28th in sack rate but added Olivier Vernon and Sheldon Richardson in the offseason. They join Myles Garrett, Denzel Ward, Joe Schobert and Greedy Williams to lead what is a solid but not flawless unit. Especially with a Week 1 home matchup against Tennessee on tap, Cleveland is an intriguing 2019 sleeper D/ST.

Crosby was fantasy's No. 7 kicker in 2018 after finishing 16th or worse each of the previous three seasons. He attempted 37 field goals, which tied for his second most in a single season in his 12-year career. Crosby has benefited from plenty of opportunity in Green Bay's high-scoring offense, but efficiency has eluded him nearly his entire career. He made 30 of 37 attempts last season (81.1 percent) and, in terms of expected conversion rate based on distance, Crosby has been below average in nine of 12 seasons, including each of the past three. Crosby is a fringe fantasy starter and loses some value in leagues that dock for misses.

Baltimore attacked wide receiver early in April's draft, but Snead still came out as the team's primary slot receiver. The 26-year-old ranked 32nd in the league with 95 targets last season, but his short-area role (8.6 aDOT) allowed only 651 yards (50th). He managed only one touchdown thanks to one end zone target and a 1.9 OTD. Snead's 1.1 touchdown rate was worst at the position and he has yet to eclipse four touchdowns in a single season in his career. Snead could soak up a decent target share in Baltimore this season, but the combination of the Ravens' extremely run-heavy offense, Lamar Jackson's inaccuracies and Snead's minimal role near the goal line leaves him with little fantasy appeal. He has barely worth a look in deep PPR leagues.

Doctson is back for a make-or-break fourth NFL season after a disappointing start to his career. The 2016 first-round pick missed all but 30 snaps of his rookie season (Achilles injury) and has posted lines of 35/502/6 and 44/532/2 on 76 targets during each of the past two seasons. Doctson appeared to be developing into a force near the goal line in 2017 when he handled 17 end zone targets (sixth most), but he saw only six in 2018. He has caught 52 percent of his career targets and is averaging a weak 7.0 YPT. Doctson is now 26 years old, but is in line for one more shot as Washington's No. 1 wide receiver. He's worth post-hype consideration in deep leagues.

Last season's Mr. Irrelevant, Quinn was the final pick of the 2018 draft. Two injuries derailed his rookie campaign, but Quinn did flash in his only two full games. He posted a 9/75/1 line on 10 targets and was fantasy's No. 33 wide receiver. Quinn is the in-house favorite to replace Jamison Crowder as Washington's slot receiver between Josh Doctson and Paul Richardson, though he'll also need to fend off rookies Terry McLaurin and Kelvin Harmon. Docston's struggles combined with the durability concerns of Richardson and Jordan Reed open the door for Quinn to sneak into a big role in his second season. He's an intriguing sleeper in deep PPR leagues.

Agholor's 2017 season felt like a success and his 2018 a disappointment, but his production was closer than you probably realize. The 2015 first-round pick posted a 62/768/8 line during a breakout 2017 season, but his 5.0 OTD suggested touchdown regression to the mean was on tap. Sure enough, the Eagles slot receiver posted a similar 64/743/4 line in 2018 with touchdowns being the notable exception. Agholor still managed a 34th-place finish in fantasy points (he was 23rd in 2017), though half of his four weekly finishes better than 38th came in Weeks 16-17. The 26-year-old still has a role in a good Eagles offense, but he has a lot of competition for targets with DeSean Jackson and J.J. Arcega-Whiteside now in the fold and Dallas Goedert entering his second season. Agholor is fine bench depth, but not a weekly starter.

Ross made his name with a record 4.22-second 40-yard dash at the 2017 NFL combine, but his career is off to a rough start. Ross battled through injuries and fumbled on his only touch as a rookie before posting a bizarre 21/210/7 line on 58 targets in 2018. The 2017 ninth overall pick caught 36 percent of his targets and averaged 3.6 YPT, both of which were worst at the position. Granted, a league-high 36 percent of balls thrown his way were off target, but Ross averaged only 10.0 YPR despite a 13.9 aDOT (15th highest). He scored seven touchdowns, but his 4.8 OTD suggests that's unsustainable. Durability is a major concern for the 23-year-old, as he already has missed 16 games with various injuries. He could still turn the corner, but he's no more than a dynasty stash.

Foster signed with the Bills as an undrafted free agent last offseason and ended up working his way into an every-down role for Buffalo's final four games. He posted a 19/285/2 line and was fantasy's No. 18 wide receiver on 25 targets during the span. Foster's rookie-season rate stats were off the charts, as he posted a 21.3 aDOT, 20.1 YPR and 11.9 YPT. Foster is entering his second NFL season, though he's already 25 years old. With John Brown and Cole Beasley added, Foster figures to compete with Zay Jones for No. 3 duties. It's not an ideal situation in Buffalo's run-heavy offense, but Foster can't be completely ignored after an explosive finish to his rookie season. Keep him stashed in dynasty.

The Eagles selected Arcega-Whiteside in the second round of April's draft. He joins a deep wide receiver group that also includes Alshon Jeffery, DeSean Jackson and Nelson Agholor. Arcega-Whiteside is a big (6-foot-2, 225 pounds), strong weapon who thrives on contested catches and jump balls, especially near the goal line (only two players eclipsed his 14 touchdown catches last season). The Stanford product lacks top-end speed and isn't particularly dynamic with the ball in his hands (4.1 RAC last season), but he makes up for it with tremendous ball skills and good hands (he dropped one of 75 catchable passes in 2018). With the aforementioned trio, as well as Zach Ertz and Dallas Goedert in the mix for targets, Arcega-Whiteside will need an injury or two to enter the fantasy landscape in 2019. This is a good landing spot for his dynasty value, however.

The Steelers drafted Johnson with the No. 66 pick of April's draft. The Toledo product will be counted on to help replace Antonio Brown, whom Pittsburgh traded to Oakland earlier in the offseason. Johnson is a small receiver (5-foot-10, 183 pounds) with good quickness, playmaking ability and post-catch skill (8.5 RAC in 2018). Johnson played both the slot (37 percent in 2018) and perimeter at Toledo, while contributing as a receiver (225 targets) and returner (79 kick, 17 punt) during his three seasons. His hands need work (seven drops last season) and he disappointed at the combine, especially in the 40-yard dash (4.53). Pittsburgh is terrific at developing wide receivers, so this is a good long-term landing spot for Johnson, but he figures to work as a situational receiver and returner in 2019.

Despite a very shaky group of wide receivers, the Raiders ranked 18th in three-plus wide receiver sets last season (76%). In coach Jon Gruden and OC Greg Olson's second season with the team, we should expect that number to rise (perhaps significantly) with Antonio Brown, Tyrell Williams, J.J. Nelson, Ryan Grant and Renfrow added to the fold. Renfrow was selected by Oakland in the fifth round of April's draft. The 5-foot-10, 184-pound Clemson product has a path to a significant rookie season role with the team's slot gig up for grabs between Brown and Williams. Renfrow is an underrated dynasty hold and could sneak into value in deep PPR leagues in 2019.

Riddick failed to score a touchdown and finished 43rd among running backs in fantasy points last season. That's notable because it was the first time the standout receiving back failed to score at least three touchdowns since 2013 and the first time he failed to finish 26th or better in fantasy since 2014. Although his 5.2 YPT was a career worst, Riddick caught 61 passes last season, which was ninth-most at the position and the second-highest total of his career. The past four seasons, Riddick ranks second at the position in targets (309), first in receptions (247), third in receiving yards (1896) and fifth in touchdown catches (10). The 28-year-old back is on a new roster, but he figures to remain busy in passing situations, which gives him some value in deep PPR leagues.

Burkhead has appeared in 23 games across two seasons with the Patriots, handling roughly one quarter of the carries and just under 10 percent of the targets during both seasons. Last season's 3.3 YPC was both the worst of his career and fourth-worst at the position, but note that he has finished second and first, respectively, in average box defenders each of the past two seasons. The 29-year-old is a competent rusher and effective receiver with a defined role in one of the league's best offenses. He has little standalone value, and that's doubtful to change with James White, Sony Michel and Damien Harris all on the roster.

Montgomery signed with the Jets and is expected to work as a passing-down complement to Le'Veon Bell this season. A third-round pick in 2015, Montgomery has bounced between wide receiver and running during stints with the Packers and Ravens over the past four seasons. Though he is averaging a healthy 4.7 YPC in his career, Montgomery has never cleared 102 carries in a season. That's unlikely to change in 2019, even if Bell misses time with an injury. The versatile Montgomery figures to soak up only a handful of touches most weeks, though Jets coach Adam Gase found creative paths to big plays for Albert Wilson and Jakeem Grant in Miami, and Montgomery figures to be ticketed for some of those opportunities. Montgomery has minimal fantasy value even if he beats out Elijah McGuire, Bilal Powell and Trenton Cannon for the No. 2 gig.

Allen's rookie season was as expected on one hand and anything but on the other. The expected part was his struggles as a passer. Allen posted an ugly 10-to-12 TD/INT mark and ranked dead last in both completion percentage (53 percent) and off-target rate (22 percent). His 6.5 yards per attempt was fourth worst despite a league-high 11.2 aDOT. The surprising aspect was Allen's elite rushing production. Allen carried the ball 89 times for 631 yards and 8 touchdowns and his 7.1 yards per carry topped the position. The latter allowed Allen the most fantasy points at the position once he returned from injury in Week 12 through Week 17. Allen's passing struggles make him a risky fantasy investment, but he's worth a late-round flier because of his rushing contributions.

After finishing worse than ninth among quarterbacks in fantasy points once during the previous seven seasons, Stafford plummeted to a 20th-place finish in Matt Patricia's first season as Detroit's head coach in 2018. Volume was one of the culprits, as Stafford failed to finish top 10 in dropbacks, pass attempts and passing yardage for the first time since 2010. Efficiency was also an issue, as Stafford was off target on 19 percent of his throws (sixth worst) and posted 6.81 yards per attempt (worst since his rookie season in 2009). Stafford is still in his prime at 31 years old, but has evolved into a conservative passer (6.8 aDOT was third lowest last season). He offers little with his legs with 54 attempts, 169 yards and zero touchdowns over the past two seasons. He's a back-end QB2 with limited upside in Detroit's run-first offense.

Mariota is entering his fifth NFL season, but has yet to play a full 16-game regular season and has never finished a campaign better than 12th in fantasy points. He's a tough read, as he shines in some areas (no worse than the 64th percentile in adjusted completion rate and better than average in yards per attempt in each of his four seasons) and struggles in others (24 TDs, 23 INTs over the past two seasons). Despite missing four games during the span, Mariota has ranked no lower than eighth in carries and rushing yards at the position each of the past three seasons. He lacks upside in Tennessee's run-heavy offense and is best viewed as a fringe QB2.

Eifert has been a fantasy force when healthy, but that hasn't been the case much during his six seasons in the league. The 2013 first-round pick has never appeared in a full 16-game regular season, managing to play only 43 (or 45 percent) of a possible 96 games. Eifert missed three games in 2015 but still led the league with 13 touchdowns. He missed eight games in 2016 but scored five touchdowns and ranked seventh at the position in fantasy points per game. In 2018, Eifert posted back-to-back top-seven fantasy weeks before going down with an ankle injury after four games. Eifert's durability is obviously a major concern, but the 28-year-old has enough upside to warrant a late-round flier.

Miami selected Gesicki in the second round of the 2018 draft and allowed him 205 routes (38th most) in a situational role during his rookie campaign. Gesicki posted a 22-202-0 line on 32 targets. Despite an 8.6 aDOT (13th highest), Gesicki averaged an ugly 9.2 YPR (fourth lowest) and 6.3 YPT (eighth lowest). The speedy, athletic 23-year-old is a candidate for a larger role in his second season, with newcomer Dwayne Allen likely to focus on blocking. Gesicki is worth a late-round flier in deeper leagues.

Dissly took the fantasy landscape by storm last season, as the relatively unheralded rookie tight end exploded for a 6-147-2 line and the third-most fantasy points at the position through Week 2. Dissly predictably came back to earth a bit in Week 3 before suffering a season-ending knee injury in Week 4. The 2018 fourth-round pick was targeted 13 times through three weeks (third most on the team), though he ran a route on only 53 percent of the team's pass plays. Dissly figures to take on a larger role in his second season, which makes him a fine late flier, but Seattle's run-heavy offense will limit his upside.
